{{Duplication|dupe=confusion_matrix|date=September 2018}}A '''confusion network''' is a [[natural language processing]] method that combines outputs from multiple machine translation systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rosti|first=Antti-Veikko I.|last2=Zhang|first2=Bing|last3=Matsoukas|first3=Spyros|last4=Schwartz|first4=Richard|date=2008|title=Incremental Hypothesis Alignment for Building Confusion Networks with Application to Machine Translation System Combination|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1626394.1626423|journal=Proceedings of the Third Workshop on Statistical Machine Translation|series=StatMT '08|location=Stroudsburg, PA, USA|publisher=Association for Computational Linguistics|pages=183–186|isbn=9781932432091}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matusov|first=Evgeny|last2=Ueffing|first2=Nicola|last3=Ney|first3=Hermann|date=2006|title=Computing consensus translation from multiple machine translation systems using enhanced hypotheses alignment|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/summary?doi=10.1.1.483.5417|journal=In Proc. EACL}}</ref> The defining characteristic of confusion networks is that they allow multiple ambiguous inputs, deferring committal translation decisions until later stages of processing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hoang|first=Hieu|date=2007|title=Factored translation models|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/summary?doi=10.1.1.80.3572|journal=In Proceedings of the 2007 Joint Conference on Empirical Methods in Natural Language Processing and Computational Natural Language Learning (EMNLP-CoNLL|pages=868–876}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koehn|first=Philipp|last2=Hoang|first2=Hieu|last3=Birch|first3=Alexandra|last4=Callison-Burch|first4=Chris|last5=Federico|first5=Marcello|last6=Bertoldi|first6=Nicola|last7=Cowan|first7=Brooke|last8=Shen|first8=Wade|last9=Moran|first9=Christine|date=2007|title=Moses: Open Source Toolkit for Statistical Machine Translation|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1557769.1557821|journal=Proceedings of the 45th Annual Meeting of the ACL on Interactive Poster and Demonstration Sessions|series=ACL '07|location=Stroudsburg, PA, USA|publisher=Association for Computational Linguistics|pages=177–180}}</ref> This approach is used in the [[Open-source software|open source]] [[machine translation]] software [[Moses (machine translation)|Moses]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statmt.org/moses/?n=Moses.ConfusionNetworks|title=Moses - Moses/ConfusionNetworks|website=www.statmt.org|access-date=2017-11-09}}</ref> and the [[Proprietary software|proprietary]] translation API in [[Bluemix|IBM Bluemix]] [[Watson (computer)|Watson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibm.com/watson/developercloud/speech-to-text/api/v1/|title=IBM® Speech to Text service provides an API Reference {{!}} IBM Watson Developer Cloud|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ibm.com|language=en|archive-url=https://archive.is/B7rkE|archive-date=2017-11-09|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-09|quote=A confidence value that is the lower bound for identifying a hypothesis as a possible word alternative (also known as "Confusion Networks"). An alternative word is considered if its confidence is greater than or equal to the threshold. Specify a probability between 0 and 1 inclusive. No alternative words are computed if you omit the parameter.}}</ref>
